1. We have a table Calculator with columns: 

(
 Id number, 
 PId number, 
 Ca_Vid_Id number, 
 CA_ACTIVE char(1),  -- Active - Y, Not Active - N  
 Name varchar2(500), 
 Value varchar2(500)
)

- Task: Select all active calculators with Ca_Vid_Id = 1;
	Command:
SELECT *
FROM Calculator
WHERE Ca_Vid_Id = 1 AND CA_ACTIVE = ‘Y’;

2. We have a table agreement with columns:

( 
  id number -- id of entity (agreement/ add. agreement)  
  pId number -- id of agreement for add. agreement
  dateCreate date                -- date of creation
  premium number                 -- bonus for agreement
)

- Task: Select all agreements that contain add. agreements created since 01.12.2020;
	Command:
SELECT DISTINCT a.*
FROM agreement a
JOIN agreement add_ag ON a.id = add_ag.pId
WHERE add_ag.dateCreate >= ‘2020-12-01’;

- Task: Count the sum of premium for all agreements since 01.12.2020;
	Command:
​​SELECT SUM(premium) AS total_premium
FROM agreement
WHERE dateCreate >= ‘2020-12-01’;


- Task: Count the number of agreements with a premium of more than $1000 and created after 01.12.2020;
	Command:
SELECT COUNT(*) AS agreements_count
FROM agreement
WHERE premium > 1000 AND dateCreate >= ‘2020-12-01’;



3. Select all users whose email does not end with @gmail.com.
	Command:
SELECT username
FROM users
WHERE email NOT LIKE '%@gmail.com';

4. Select all articles that were written by user 1test and created between 2020-07-5 and 2020-07-7 (included), and order by a descending created date.
	Command:
SELECT a.*, u.username
FROM article a
JOIN userprofile up ON a.author_id = u.id
JOIN users u ON a.author_id = up.id
WHERE u.username = '1test'
AND DATE (a.createdAT) BETWEEN '2020-07-05' AND '2020-07-07'
ORDER BY a.createdAt DESC;

5. Select the usernames of users and the number of articles written by these users.
	Command:
SELECT u.username, COUNT(a.id) AS articles_coumt
FROM users u
JOIN userprofile up ON u.id = up.user_id
LEFT JOIN article a ON a.author_id = up.id
GROUP BY u.username;

6. Select all users who have favorite articles. Print username and article_title columns.
	Command:
SELECT u.username, a.title AS article_title
FROM favoritor_assoc f
JOIN usersprofile up ON f.favoriter = u.id
JOIN users u ON up.user_id = u.id
JOIN article a ON f.favorited_article = a.id;
